We can advertise topics with the same names but different topic types:
```
#!c++

ignition::transport::Node node;
auto pubId = node.Advertise<ignition::msgs::StringMsg>(topic);
auto pubId1 = node.Advertise<ignition::msgs::Int32>(topic);
```
Now there is a problem with publishing:


```
#!c++

  // Prepare the message.
  ignition::msgs::StringMsg msg;
  ignition::msgs::Int32 msg1;
  msg.set_data("HELLO");
  msg1.set_data(12);

  node.Publish(pubId, msg);
  node.Publish(pubId1, msg1);
```
Console:


```
#!bash

$ ./publisher 
Node::Publish() Type mismatch.
	* Type advertised: ignition.msgs.StringMsg
	* Type published: ignition.msgs.Int32
```

Source file is attached.

I am using a service call to reset the Gazebo8 simulation. I want to make sure that the simulation is reset, or else the simulation should crash. Because of that, I am not sending any requests, and I don't really need a reply - I only need to check if executed is true, so the reply is Empty.

This is the client side:


```
#!c++
void reset_cli() {
  ignition::msgs::Empty rep;

  bool result;
  unsigned int timeout = 60000;

  std::cerr << "REQ" << std::endl;
  bool executed = node_.Request("/reset", timeout, rep, result);
  std::cerr << "REQX" << " " << executed << std::endl;
}

```

and this is the server side:


```
#!c++

void reset_srv(ignition::msgs::Empty& rep, bool& result) {
  std::cerr << "REP" << std::endl;
  world_->Reset();
  std::cerr << "REPX" << std::endl;
  result = true;
}
```

This is the output that I receive:


```
